==English==

===Etymology===
From Middle English, from Old English ''[[broðor|brōðor]]''. Cognates include Latin ''[[frater]]'', Greek ''[[φρατηρ]]'' (phrater), Gothic ''[[𐌱𐍂𐍉𐌸𐌰𐍂]]'' (broþar), German ''[[Bruder]]'', Russian ''[[брат]]'' (brat).

===Pronunciation===
*AHD: brŭ''th'''ə(r)
*IPA: /ˈbrʌðə(r)/
*SAMPA: "brVD@(r)/

===Noun===
'''brother'''  (''plural:'' '''[[brothers]]''' ''or'' '''[[brethren]]''')

# Someone’s male [[sibling]].
# A male having at least one [[parent]] in common with another, see [[half-brother]], [[stepbrother]].
# A male fellow member of a religious community or church.  (''plural:'' [[brethren]] or [[brothers]])
# Someone who is a [[peer]], whether male or female.  (''plural:'' [[brethren]] or [[brothers]])

===Usage note===
<!--Usage note belongs in [[brothers]] (also?)-->
The plural "brethren" tends to be used more in broader senses than in familial ones.

